# CursorRules.md

Version: V1.0

Project: Automated Score Input Tools (ASIT)

---

# 1. Purpose

This document defines the development rules that Cursor AI must follow throughout the ASIT project.

The purpose is to ensure:

* Consistent architecture
* Stable code quality
* Reusable modules
* Predictable project structure
* Long-term maintainability

These rules have higher priority than temporary implementation decisions.

When conflicts occur:

PRD > Cursor Rules > AI Suggestions

---

# 2. General Principles

Cursor must always follow these principles:

1. Read before writing.
2. Reuse before creating.
3. Think before modifying.
4. Never guess business rules.
5. Never hardcode business data.
6. Keep modules independent.
7. Keep code readable.
8. Prefer simplicity over cleverness.

---

# 3. Project Understanding

Before writing any code, Cursor must understand that ASIT is:

* A desktop application.
* Windows first.
* Future cross-platform.
* Excel-driven.
* Rule-driven.
* Offline-first.
* Business-oriented.

The Scoring Rules are NOT code.

The Excel Rule File defines business behavior.

---

# 4. Development Workflow

Every task must follow:

Step 1

Read PRD.

↓

Step 2

Locate related modules.

↓

Step 3

Search existing implementation.

↓

Step 4

Reuse existing code.

↓

Step 5

Write implementation.

↓

Step 6

Run self-check.

↓

Step 7

Update documentation if necessary.

Cursor must never skip steps.

---

# 5. File Creation Rules

Before creating any file:

Cursor must answer:

* Does similar functionality already exist?
* Can this file extend an existing module?
* Can this be solved inside an existing class?

If YES:

Do NOT create a new file.

Examples of forbidden filenames:

utils2.ts

utils-new.ts

helper.ts

common2.ts

temp.ts

test-new.ts

---

# 6. Code Modification Rules

Prefer modifying existing modules.

Do not duplicate logic.

Forbidden:

ScoringEngine2

ScoreCalculator

ExcelParserNew

ValidationV2

Instead:

Improve existing implementation.

---

# 7. Architecture Rules

Cursor must never break architecture boundaries.

UI

↓

Application

↓

Domain

↓

Infrastructure

Forbidden:

UI directly reading Excel.

UI calculating scores.

UI modifying configuration.

Infrastructure calling UI.

Circular dependencies.

---

# 8. Business Logic Rules

Business logic belongs ONLY inside Domain.

Forbidden locations:

React Component

Electron Window

Dialog

Toolbar

Context Menu

Every calculation must go through:

Scoring Engine.

---

# 9. Excel Rules

All Excel operations belong only to:

Excel Parser

Export Engine

Forbidden:

xlsx.read()

inside UI.

Direct worksheet manipulation outside infrastructure.

---

# 10. Rule File Rules

Never hardcode:

Score

Distance

Time

Grade

Weight

Everything comes from:

Rule Manager.

---

# 11. TypeScript Rules

Forbidden:

* any
* unknown abuse
* implicit any
* magic numbers
* magic strings

Required:

Strict typing.

Interfaces.

Enums where appropriate.

Readonly where possible.

---

# 12. Naming Rules

Classes

PascalCase

Interfaces

IPascalCase (or PascalCase, depending on project convention)

Functions

camelCase

Constants

UPPER_SNAKE_CASE

Files

kebab-case

Folders

lowercase

---

# 13. Error Handling Rules

Never ignore exceptions.

Forbidden:

catch {}

Required:

* Catch
* Log
* Return typed error
* Show user-friendly message

---

# 14. Logging Rules

Never use console.log() as production logging.

Use LogManager only.

Every error must have:

* Timestamp
* Module
* Error Code
* Description

---

# 15. Performance Rules

Avoid:

Repeated Excel parsing.

Repeated Rule loading.

Repeated object creation.

Prefer:

Caching.

Lazy loading.

Object reuse.

---

# 16. Refactoring Rules

Refactoring must NOT change behavior.

Required:

* Same input
* Same output
* Same business result

Run tests before completion.

---

# 17. Testing Rules

Every business feature requires:

* Unit tests
* Boundary tests
* Exception tests

Scoring Engine must maintain 100% test coverage.

---

# 18. Git Rules

Commit format:

feat:

fix:

docs:

refactor:

test:

style:

No unrelated changes in a single commit.

---

# 19. Documentation Rules

Whenever business behavior changes:

Update:

* PRD
* Architecture
* Test Cases

Code without documentation updates is considered incomplete.

---

# 20. AI Self-Checklist

Before finishing any task, Cursor must verify:

□ No duplicated code

□ No architecture violation

□ No hardcoded business data

□ Reused existing modules

□ Passed TypeScript checks

□ Passed lint checks

□ Tests updated

□ Documentation updated

□ PRD still satisfied

Only after every item is satisfied may the task be considered complete.

---

# 21. Absolute Prohibitions

Cursor must NEVER:

* Hardcode score tables.
* Hardcode Excel headers.
* Modify scoring algorithms without PRD updates.
* Bypass validation.
* Bypass audit.
* Modify original Excel files.
* Break architecture.
* Duplicate business logic.
* Introduce circular dependencies.
* Guess undefined business rules.

When requirements are unclear:

STOP.

Ask for clarification.

Never assume.
